Raw dev notes -- RAG Pipeline: Fighting Segfaults and Finding Structure

Okay, so this past week has been a deep dive into building out this new RAG pipeline. The project, which I'm calling the "bidi-doc-rag-pipeline" (a bit of a mouthful, I know), is all about making sense of really complex, often cross-referenced documentation. Think manuals, technical specs, things where understanding one part often requires jumping to another, or where the context isn't just linear. The goal is to build a system that can answer questions accurately by intelligently pulling context from these dense documents, even when they're messy.

The initial commit was just getting the repo set up, but things quickly ramped up. The first big chunk of work was laying down the core architecture and getting the initial data ingestion going. This included building out a "corpus expansion pipeline." The idea here is that the initial set of documents might not be enough, or they might link to other relevant documents. So, this pipeline is designed to intelligently find and incorporate more related content, essentially growing our knowledge base. Crucially, I also started implementing the "cross-reference graph." This is super important for the "bidirectional" aspect – it's about mapping out how different sections, documents, or concepts link to each other. Without this, the RAG system would just be pulling isolated chunks of text, which isn't going to cut it for complex docs. Getting the basic structure of this graph in place was a big milestone.

Then came the real fun: "hardening extraction." Oh boy. This is where the rubber meets the road when you're dealing with real-world documents. My initial extraction methods, while fine for clean text, started falling apart with some of the gnarlier inputs. The biggest headache was definitely the "segfault protection." I was getting crashes, hard crashes, which usually means some underlying C/C++ library I'm using for document parsing is hitting bad memory or malformed data. Debugging segfaults is never fun; it's like trying to find a needle in a haystack while the haystack is on fire. It took a lot of defensive programming, trying different parsing strategies, and adding robust error handling around the document processing steps. It felt like I was constantly patching holes in a leaky boat.

Alongside that, I realized I couldn't just trust the output. So, I implemented an "auto quality check" for the extracted content. This is a set of heuristics and checks to make sure the text that comes out isn't garbled, missing huge chunks, or just plain nonsense. It's a sanity check to ensure the RAG system isn't fed garbage. And finally, "heading detection" was a critical addition. For structured documents, knowing what's a main heading, a subheading, or just body text is vital for providing good context. Initially, the extractor was a bit dumb about this, but now it's much smarter, which should significantly improve retrieval quality.

Honestly, this past week felt like a rollercoaster. There were moments of pure frustration, especially with those segfaults. I felt like I was banging my head against a wall trying to figure out why things were crashing. But then, when I finally tracked down a tricky bug or saw the auto quality check correctly flag a bad extraction, there was a real sense of accomplishment. It's a good reminder that building robust systems isn't just about getting the happy path working; it's about anticipating all the ways things can go wrong and building safeguards. It really hammered home the importance of defensive programming and understanding the limitations of external libraries. It also reinforced that data quality is paramount – garbage in, garbage out, even with the smartest RAG model.

Next up: Integrating the refined extraction with the cross-reference graph for initial RAG queries.
